This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Science sub-category of Network and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) as it deals with the customization of multi-tenant service networks. It could also belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category as it involves the coordination of services in a network. Additionally, it could be classified under Software Engineering (cs.SE) as it proposes an approach to simplify the customization process for tenants. The paper also involves system-level design and control, which could place it under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, it could be classified under Programming Languages (cs.PL) as it proposes the use of features as a high-level customization abstraction.
